run the risk of freezing my feet and turn
back rather than continue to the summit.

226
00:14:51,950 --> 00:14:57,200
An amazing experience which I had not
anticipated but did a number of times was,

227
00:14:58,250 --> 00:15:03,450
climbing with the oxygen off and then
turning the oxygen supply on.

228
00:15:03,450 --> 00:15:08,170
And it was to two liters per minute flow
rate, which is very modest.

229
00:15:08,170 --> 00:15:13,380
I mean, it's a low, a low oxygen
supplementation flow rate.

230
00:15:15,160 --> 00:15:19,650
The only way to describe it was, this is
like, the sensation which I'd never

231
00:15:19,650 --> 00:15:26,040
imagined I'd be able to have, which is of,
the, the sensation of aerobic metabolism.

232
00:15:26,040 --> 00:15:30,710
The equivalent would be as if somebody
took a perfect,

233
00:15:30,710 --> 00:15:36,820
like 100 degree bucket of water and poured
it in into one's belly.

234
00:15:36,820 --> 00:15:41,920
This sensation of warmth emanating from my
core when

235
00:15:41,920 --> 00:15:45,760
I would turn the oxygen back on, it was
very interesting.

236
00:15:45,760 --> 00:15:49,495
Which of course made me, the physician,
shut it off.

237
00:15:49,495 --> 00:15:52,180
>> [LAUGH].
>> And then turn it back on [CROSSTALK] to

238
00:15:52,180 --> 00:15:54,340
get that cool sensation and

239
00:15:54,340 --> 00:16:00,330
I mentioned it to co-climbers of, how
amazing it was that you can actually feel

240
00:16:00,330 --> 00:16:05,749
the improvement of aerobic metabolism and
generation of body heat.

241
00:16:06,800 --> 00:16:10,700
Which I'd never thought and I've
subsequently learned, yeah of course,

242
00:16:10,700 --> 00:16:16,000
people have noticed this before doing
exactly that at extremes of altitude.

243
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:19,510
But it's an amazing sensation which it'd
be really hard to duplicate down

244
00:16:19,510 --> 00:16:24,930
here except in like the Army labs
environment, where the Operation Everest.

245
00:16:26,050 --> 00:16:27,320
I don't know whether they tried it,

246
00:16:27,320 --> 00:16:29,795
but I suspect if they had, they probably
had the same experience.

247
00:16:29,795 --> 00:16:30,440
>> Mm-hm.

248
00:16:30,440 --> 00:16:33,050
Yeah, and also knowing it and experiencing
it are two different things.

249
00:16:33,050 --> 00:16:35,170
So, intellectually you could know that's
going to happen, but

250
00:16:35,170 --> 00:16:36,680
to feel that flush, that must be amazing.

251
00:16:38,090 --> 00:16:40,370
>> Yeah the, you know, when you're hand-,
you're out, you know,

252
00:16:40,370 --> 00:16:43,280
throwing snowballs as a kid, and you go
back in, and your hands warm up,

253
00:16:43,280 --> 00:16:47,650
and they tingle, and then they feel so
nice and glowing warm, kind of like that.

254
00:16:47,650 --> 00:16:49,710
But it was in your core.

255
00:16:49,710 --> 00:16:52,260
I mean, it's an amazing experience.

