273
00:18:04,420 --> 00:18:10,010
He became sick with some dehydration,

274
00:18:10,010 --> 00:18:14,560
and probably evolution of high altitude
cerebral edema.

275
00:18:14,560 --> 00:18:20,768
Like a, a brain related hypoxic injury
circumstance can be devastating and

276
00:18:20,768 --> 00:18:25,600
fatal, including in a fairly short period
of time.

277
00:18:25,600 --> 00:18:30,480
Which actually was what killed Rob Hall's

278
00:18:30,480 --> 00:18:35,050
climbing partner and ultimately guiding
partner, a guy named Gary Ball,

279
00:18:35,050 --> 00:18:40,030
who died on Gashiram Four, in Pakistan of
acute cerebral edema.

280
00:18:40,030 --> 00:18:42,370
He was sick, didn't feel so good.

281
00:18:42,370 --> 00:18:46,170
And when the sun went down, and he was
dead by the time the sun came up.

282
00:18:47,380 --> 00:18:51,256
So the Spanish climber got sick, was
stumbling, and had cerebral edema, and

283
00:18:51,256 --> 00:18:56,010
I had to spend a lot of time helping him
get down and ultimately off the mountain.

284
00:18:56,010 --> 00:18:57,900
So that chewed up a, a fair bit of time.

285
00:18:57,900 --> 00:19:06,150
And then the other full-sail absolute
disaster was a Slovak

286
00:19:06,150 --> 00:19:13,360
climbing team came up and set off to do a
fast alpine, oxygen free

287
00:19:13,360 --> 00:19:18,910
ascent of the southwest face of Everest,
which takes off right above this camp.

288
00:19:18,910 --> 00:19:21,460
And we loaned them a radio so

289
00:19:21,460 --> 00:19:24,249
that they could be in contact with people
including base camp.

290
00:19:25,720 --> 00:19:32,230
And, unfortunately what we were able then
to witness was the slow disintegration and

291
00:19:32,230 --> 00:19:34,090
ultimately death of all four of them.

292
00:19:35,230 --> 00:19:40,560
Initially getting sick on the very upper
edges of the southwest face.

293
00:19:42,010 --> 00:19:46,360
One, then two behind, one finally went to
the summit.

294
00:19:46,360 --> 00:19:50,610
And they all four then were going to try
to descend and they were asking for

295
00:19:50,610 --> 00:19:54,770
us to help to find them because they were
going to be coming down the route

296
00:19:54,770 --> 00:19:57,936
that we would try to ascend that night.

297
00:19:57,936 --> 00:20:02,590
And bad storms and they were, you know,
making radio

298
00:20:02,590 --> 00:20:05,820
calls to try to get us to help them saying
they'll leave their head lamps on.

299
00:20:05,820 --> 00:20:09,990
And they probably got blown off the ridge
later, but none of them were recovered.

300
00:20:09,990 --> 00:20:11,330
>> It must be so

301
00:20:11,330 --> 00:20:15,540
hard to listen to that from afar, and hear
everything going wrong and be so helpless.

302
00:20:15,540 --> 00:20:18,080
>> And here the voice, and hear the voice
of a dying person.

303
00:20:18,080 --> 00:20:19,160
>> Yeah.
>> They were,

304
00:20:19,160 --> 00:20:21,140
they were definitely in dire straights.

305
00:20:21,140 --> 00:20:25,500
It was, it was quite clear even before
they said they were in dire straights,

306
00:20:25,500 --> 00:20:30,530
that they were in, in a deep bit of
disaster.

307
00:20:30,530 --> 00:20:35,320
And that was, between them, they had over
20 ascents of

308
00:20:35,320 --> 00:20:40,540
peaks of 8,000 meters and they were, they
were very experienced climbers.

309
00:20:40,540 --> 00:20:45,105
And they were just in the wrong
circumstance, at the wrong time.

310
00:20:45,105 --> 00:20:46,150
>> Mm-hm.

311
00:20:46,150 --> 00:20:50,330
>> And the margins, again it's, it's a
very big peak.

312
00:20:50,330 --> 00:20:55,470
It's not technically that tricky to climb,
particularly by those routes but it's,

313
00:20:55,470 --> 00:21:00,720
it's very high and it's the hypoxia that,
that leaves really no margins.

314
00:21:01,840 --> 00:21:05,720
>> So on Everest, were there people that
you encountered either in the camps or

315
00:21:05,720 --> 00:21:09,280
in your own team, that you looked at and
talked with and

316
00:21:09,280 --> 00:21:12,760
thought, ooh, you know, they, they're on
their way to being in trouble.

317
00:21:12,760 --> 00:21:16,830
Either because of their problems with
cognitive function or symptoms and

318
00:21:16,830 --> 00:21:18,685
you thought that they should, really
should be going down and

319
00:21:18,685 --> 00:21:21,700
you, have you had to make a call for
anyone else like that?

320
00:21:24,480 --> 00:21:27,040
>> No, with one exception.

321
00:21:27,040 --> 00:21:34,850
So my time on Everest was before the era
of commercial expeditions to Everest.

322
00:21:36,290 --> 00:21:41,080
As a doc, I don't think I'd want to find
myself remotely close to Everest Base Camp

323
00:21:41,080 --> 00:21:46,540
now, because I might be frightened at the
broad range, much broader range of

324
00:21:46,540 --> 00:21:52,210
experience, and climbing skill, and time
in the mountains.

325
00:21:52,210 --> 00:21:57,350
And might be much more frightened by some
people who have relatively less experience

326
00:21:57,350 --> 00:22:03,610
and are thus, maybe unwittingly, at the
mercy of the elements and

327
00:22:03,610 --> 00:22:07,480
a guide much more than I would ever want
to find myself.

328
00:22:07,480 --> 00:22:10,210
So I, it's nice to go to the mountains,

329
00:22:10,210 --> 00:22:13,170
I would choose to go to anything except
Everest again.

330
00:22:13,170 --> 00:22:14,850
>> No business being there at this point,
yeah.

331
00:22:14,850 --> 00:22:19,270
>> Yeah.
We did have one, one interesting

332
00:22:19,270 --> 00:22:23,658
experience, which is sort of a nice little
physiologic quirk.

333
00:22:23,658 --> 00:22:30,460
Which is a, a really terrific ranked long
distance runner

334
00:22:31,490 --> 00:22:35,990
accompanied our expedition because he
wanted to be there, not because he had

335
00:22:35,990 --> 00:22:40,450
a lot of climbing experience, but wanted
to go to Everest Base Camp.

336
00:22:40,450 --> 00:22:43,740
And along the, and he also happened to be
a doc and

337
00:22:43,740 --> 00:22:49,050
along the way, in talking, I said, well,
this is really interesting.

338
00:22:49,050 --> 00:22:54,970
because, you know, marathon runners have
fairly blunted ventilatory drives,

339
00:22:54,970 --> 00:23:02,360
they tend in general not to breathe so
rapidly in response to hypercapnia,

340
00:23:02,360 --> 00:23:08,020
CO2 going up, or hypoxia, O2 going down,
and you're one of those.

341
00:23:08,020 --> 00:23:13,970
You're an elite athlete in a different
field and your breathing response

342
00:23:13,970 --> 00:23:19,115
might well be the thing that wouldn't be
so good if you encounter extreme

343
00:23:19,115 --> 00:23:23,920
sulp-hypoxia because what you really want
to do is breathe like crazy.

344
00:23:24,960 --> 00:23:28,920
And he didn't really like the implication
that I might find that

345
00:23:28,920 --> 00:23:31,120
he was going to not do well.

346
00:23:31,120 --> 00:23:36,110
But in fact, at progressive elevation, he
just felt terrible.

347
00:23:36,110 --> 00:23:37,390
Probably because in part,

348
00:23:37,390 --> 00:23:40,450
not because he isn't a great athlete, but
because his ventilatory

349
00:23:40,450 --> 00:23:45,730
response probably makes him much more
suitable to be a marathon runner.

350
00:23:45,730 --> 00:23:49,700
Where we're clearly coming from different
flavors and, and

351
00:23:49,700 --> 00:23:54,710
our physiologic backdrop context probably
does have bearing.

352
00:23:54,710 --> 00:24:00,510
As I oftentimes say in these physiology
lectures, we are ourselves,

353
00:24:00,510 --> 00:24:03,005
and we do well that which we do well.

354
00:24:03,005 --> 00:24:06,240
>> [LAUGH]
>> You can't make me be a high speed,

355
00:24:06,240 --> 00:24:10,610
100 meter runner because I am all about
slow twitch fibers.

356
00:24:10,610 --> 00:24:15,380
And I do very well, because I pant like a
dog when I'm hypoxic.

357
00:24:15,380 --> 00:24:18,870
And that's probably why I like going to
elevation.

358
00:24:18,870 --> 00:24:19,632
because it works.

359
00:24:19,632 --> 00:24:20,430
>> Mm-hm.

360
00:24:20,430 --> 00:24:25,920
>> Whereas somebody who doesn't have that
very exquisite adaptive ventilatory

361
00:24:25,920 --> 00:24:28,270
response doesn't tend to do so well.

